Description:
[2 bladen] [blad 1, recto] General good analysis [onleesbaar] comic element: I was insisting in opposition to Friedländer and van Bastelaer, perhaps overstating my case. 1) Kermis of Hoboken (Lebeer, N°30) whether Bruegel or Hogenberg. The inscription condemns the behavior of the peasants [onleesbaar] 2) on the other hand, in the Kermis of St. George (Lebeer, N° 52) the banner is inscribed Laet die boeren haer kermis houwen; 3) Wedding Dance (Lebeer N° 61) Inscription contains no moral judgment; [toegevoegde vermelding bij de 3 punten]: 'communicated to S. Alpers in postcard 5-3-75;
[blad 1, verso] Alpers: where to be published? Comparison with other Netherlandish Kermis? Dance representation needed: Aertsen Peasant Feast, Drawing Dresden (for Vienna painting, look up), in J. Bruyn Master Drawings III/4, 165, pl. 3b (Look up Emmens on Aertsen); p. 8 doubtful. Also inscription on one of the prints: Let the peasants have their [onleesbaar][=Kermis]. Schlosser (Arme Leute Kunst) [= Julius von Schlosser, Armeleutekunst, in: Jahrbuch für Kunstsammler 1 (1921), pp. 47-66] about peasant & court to be mentioned go back to 1400; [toegevoegde vermelding]: 'F.G. Turning to Peasants rethinkable turning to vernacular in literature; p. 14/15 on relationship of observant figures-very good; [blad 2, recto] Dog toying stealing food from a basket: 1) Master of Prodigal Son (Marlier) L'Atelier du Maître du Fils Prodigue, Jaarboek 1961, Koninklijk Museum voor Schone Kunsten, p. 11, fig. 3; Maître du Fils Prodique, Les Oeuvres de Miséricorde, Valenciennes, Musée des Beaux-Arts; 2) Mandijn (Faggin) G.T. Faggin, La pittura ad Anversa al cinquecento, Florence 1918, pl. 97 Grotesque Banquet attrib. to Jan Mandijn (I am not sure) Gilboa, Museo; [blad 2, verso] de Bellas Artes. The attrib. to Mandijn is not wholly convincing.
